{
  "doc_id": "23917",
  "text": "Both factors are released via the constitutive secretory pathway in the absence of BDNF (for a review, see [CITATION_1] . NT3 increases dendritic complexity of hippocampal and cortical pyramidal cells independent of glutamate-mediated transmission [CITATION_2] Baker et al., 1998) , and NT4/5 promotes the dendritic development (this study) and the neuropeptide Y expression in the absence of activity [CITATION_3] . Although apical dendrites are fairly promiscuous, NT4/5 and NT3 are highly effective (e.g. on layer VI basal dendrites), and NT3 actions even improve in the absence of TrkB ligands [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Furthermore, layer II/III dendrites develop normally in dark-reared visual cortex [CITATION_6] despite reduced expression of BDNF, but not of other neurotrophins [CITATION_7] Ichisaka et al., 2003) , and reduced Trk receptor activation [CITATION_8] .",
